description: From Middle French stupéfier, from Latin stupefaciō (“strike dumb, stun with amazement, stupefy”), from stupeō (“I am stunned, speechless”) (English stupid, stupor) + faciō (“do, make”).

verbs.description: stupefy (third-person singular simple present stupefies, present participle stupefying, simple past and past participle stupefied)

entries.meaning: (transitive) To dull the senses or capacity to think thereby reducing responsiveness; to dazzle or stun.
